<!--
  Tomcat Context configuration (Tomcat 11.0.21+).

  CRITICAL FIX (April 2026):
  The attribute "sameSiteCookies" is not supported in Tomcat 11+ and is
  ignored (generates WARNING: "failed to set property [sameSiteCookies]").
  
  ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS:
  ────────────────────
  Tomcat's session manager adds JSESSIONID cookies OUTSIDE the Servlet filter
  chain, directly to the response connector buffer during response commit.
  This means:
  1. Tomcat's automatic JSESSIONID is NOT intercepted by response wrappers
  2. Even if SessionCookieConfig.setSameSite() worked, it wouldn't reach browsers
     on cross-origin requests without our manual cookie
  
  SOLUTION (Multi-layered defense):
  ────────────────────────────────
  1. LoginController.java: Manually creates JSESSIONID cookie with SameSite=None
     Using response.addHeader("Set-Cookie", "JSESSIONID=...; SameSite=None")
     This is added BEFORE Tomcat's automatic cookie to make it primary.
  
  2. SameSiteFilter: Still catches explicit response.addCookie() calls (like
     XSRF-TOKEN) and enhances Set-Cookie headers where possible.
  
  3. CookieConfigListener: SessionCookieConfig configuration as fallback (though
     limited in Tomcat 11+).
  
  CROSS-ORIGIN REQUIREMENTS:
  ──────────────────────────
  For Vercel (frontend) → Railway (backend) to work:
  - JSESSIONID must have SameSite=None (now: ✅ manual in LoginController)
  - XSRF-TOKEN must have SameSite=None (now: ✅ via SameSiteFilter)  
  - HTTPS required for SameSite=None (Railway: ✅ HTTPS)
  - <secure>true</secure> in web.xml (session cookie: ✅ configured)
  
  DEPLOYMENT NOTES:
  ─────────────────
  This fix ONLY works for LoginController (login endpoint). Session cookies
  created through other mechanisms may still lack SameSite=None.
  The SameSiteFilter provides defense-in-depth for any cookies created
  via response.addCookie() or response.addHeader("Set-Cookie", ...).
-->
<Context>
  <!-- Removed unsupported sameSiteCookies attribute (not recognized in Tomcat 11+) -->
  <!-- Session cookie routing is now handled in LoginController.java -->
</Context>